(922, 'wpb_js_templates', 'a:6:{s:20:\"feedstock-page_15510\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";s:14:\"Feedstock Page\";s:8:\"template\";s:1696:\"[vc_row el_position=\\\"first\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>[new_royalslider id=\\\"3\\\"]</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row] [vc_column width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>Today most agricultural production depends on petrodiesel; a convenient, but expensive fuel that poses real risks to the environment, our climate and human health. Oilseed crops on the other hand, when grown in rotation with other grains, grass and fodder are a sustainable means of producing a clean, renewable fuel to power Vermont‚Äôs agricultural sector, while generating livestock feed and food-grade oil as well. In this way, the Vermont Bioenergy Initiative is helping to put more money back in the farmers‚Äô pocket, increase their self-sufficiency, and to moderate the impacts of peak oil and climate change.</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_tabs interval=\\\"0\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [vc_tab title=\\\"Profiles\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362459966-1-58\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>Here is where the profiles will go</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_tab] [vc_tab title=\\\"Reports\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362459966-2-51\\\"] [/vc_tab] [vc_tab title=\\\"Helpful Links\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362460022419-3-8\\\"] [/vc_tab] [/vc_tabs] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row el_position=\\\"last\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_teaser_grid grid_columns_count=\\\"4\\\" grid_content=\\\"teaser\\\" grid_layout=\\\"title_thumbnail_text\\\" grid_link=\\\"link_post\\\" grid_link_target=\\\"_self\\\" grid_template=\\\"carousel\\\" grid_layout_mode=\\\"fitrows\\\" grid_thumb_size=\\\"900x617\\\" grid_posttypes=\\\"portfolio-type\\\" order=\\\"desc\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] \";}s:22:\"profilepage_1568744757\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";s:11:\"ProfilePage\";s:8:\"template\";s:324:\"[vc_row el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [vc_column el_class=\\\"ProfileMain\\\" width=\\\"2/3\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>I am text block. Click edit button to change this text.</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column el_class=\\\"ProfileSidebar\\\" el_position=\\\"last\\\" width=\\\"1/3\\\"] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] \";}s:21:\"profilepost_635820745\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";s:11:\"ProfilePost\";s:8:\"template\";s:3390:\"[vc_row el_class=\\\"ProfileText\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3><span style=\\\"text-decoration: underline;\\\">Company Profile</span></h3>\n<p><strong>Feedstock:</strong> Grass</p>\n<p><strong>Fuel:</strong> Briquettes and Pellets</p>\n<p><strong>Energy Output:</strong> Thermal (Heat and Hot Water)</p>\n<p><strong>Services:</strong> Equipment Manufacturer/Supplier, Fuel Processing, Fuel Supply</p>\n<p>RER provides customers with a complete fuel service from ‚Äúfield to flue‚Äù by producing and delivering grass pellets and briquettes and removing ash for customers. RER also works with farmers to establish grass feedstocks by developing biomass fuel standards and long-term contracts to ensure reliability for both the customer and the farmer. By establishing best practices and designing and manufacturing new processing equipment, RER has led the way to providing high-quality grass fuel to businesses and institutions.</p>\n<p><b>IMPROVING FUEL QUALITY</b></p>\n<p><a href=\\\"http://vermontbioenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/grass-p17udtae7u15vn1o6dsoe1hk91aml.jpg\\\"><img class=\\\"size-medium wp-image-5586 alignright\\\" alt=\\\"grass-p17udtae7u15vn1o6dsoe1hk91aml\\\" src=\\\"http://vermontbioenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/grass-p17udtae7u15vn1o6dsoe1hk91aml-300x211.jpg\\\" width=\\\"300\\\" height=\\\"211\\\"></a>From the start, RER recognized the need for better fuel processing protocols to improve fuel quality.</p>\n<p>RER began by collecting input from those already in the business, like current grass fuel processors, &nbsp;farmers, researchers at the University of Vermont, and experts with the United States Department of Agriculture. Their findings led to the establishment of a set of best practices and standard production protocols.</p>\n<p><b>BRINGING AN IMPROVED PRODUCT TO MARKET</b></p>\n<p>In 20xx, RER received grant funding from Vermont Sustainable Jobs Fund to design and fabricate a 2-ton per hour mobile grass briquetter, suitable for commercial production.&nbsp; The design was based on a smaller mobile unit built by BHS Energy, and purchased for use by RER to supply grass heating fuel to the Benton PA school district in 2011.</p>\n<p>Also included in the work supported by the grant from VSJF was identifying steps to build new markets for utilizing pelletized grass as a heating fuel in Vermont. [what results can we share from this work?]</p>\n<p><b>PROJECT OUTCOMES &amp; IMPACTS</b></p>\n<p>And this is what they‚Äôve learned‚Ä¶</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\\\"text-decoration: underline;\\\">Download a PDF </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><span style=\\\"text-decoration: underline;\\\">Download a PDF of RER‚Äôs final report to VSJF </span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>For further information, contact <a href=\\\"mailto:JohnBootle@Switchgrass-RER.com\\\">John Bootle</a>, (802) 379-8553 or&nbsp;<a href=\\\"mailto:Adam@Switchgrass-RER.com\\\">Adam Dantzscher</a>, (802) 578-8347.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>¬© June 2013&nbsp;. Produced by the Vermont Bioenergy Initiative, a program of the Vermont Sustainabale Jobs Fund with permission from&nbsp;Renewable Energy Resources, LLC&nbsp;and with support from the US Department of Energy&nbsp;and Vermont Senator Patrick Leahy. Permisson granted for non-commercial reproduction and use.</p>\n<div>\n<div>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] \";}s:19:\"resources_900302970\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";s:9:\"Resources\";s:8:\"template\";s:1364:\"[vc_row el_position=\\\"first\\\"] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>K-12 Teachers</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>University Professors and Researchers</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>Students</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>Farmers and Landowners</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>Ag Professionals and Extension Personnel</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>Engineers</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row el_position=\\\"last\\\"] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>Energy Program Staff</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column el_class=\\\"Resources\\\" width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <h3>Facilities Staff</h3>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] \";}s:28:\"oilseed-sub-pages_1602017160\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";s:17:\"Oilseed sub pages\";s:8:\"template\";s:1853:\"[vc_row el_position=\\\"first\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>[new_royalslider id=\\\"15\\\"]</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row] [vc_column width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p><strong>Canola</strong>, a type of rapeseed, contains approximately 43% oil, similar to the oil content of sunflowers, and more than twice the amount of oil typically found in soybeans. After oil extraction, canola meal which is sold as a livestock feed ingredient, typically contains above 35% crude protein (less than soybean and more than sunflower meal). In Europe, rapeseed is the primary source of oil used to make biodiesel, whereas canola was originally developed in Canada in the 1970‚Äôs using conventional breeding techniques in order to remove the anti-nutritional components erucic acid and glucosinolates found in rape. When canola was first introduced it was trademarked, but is now a generic term for edible varieties of rapeseed oil and meal throughout North America and Australia.Although most of the canola seed grown in North America is from genetically engineered stock (‚ÄúGMO‚Äù or ‚ÄúRoundup¬Æ Ready‚Äù), only non-GMO varieties are currently being grown on Vermont farms in small quantities.</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_tabs interval=\\\"0\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [vc_tab title=\\\"Profiles\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362459966-1-58\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>Here is where the profiles will go</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_tab] [vc_tab title=\\\"Reports\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362459966-2-51\\\"] [/vc_tab] [vc_tab title=\\\"Helpful Links\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362460022419-3-8\\\"] [/vc_tab] [/vc_tabs] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row el_position=\\\"last\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_widget_sidebar sidebar_id=\\\"sidebar-9\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] \";}s:19:\"soybeans_2095160536\";a:2:{s:4:\"name\";s:8:\"Soybeans\";s:8:\"template\";s:1940:\"[vc_row el_position=\\\"first\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>[new_royalslider id=\\\"16\\\"]</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row] [vc_column width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p><strong>Soybeans</strong>&nbsp;can grow in a variety of soils and a wide range of climates. They are a legume and contain between 13% and 18% oil. Global demand for soybeans is driven by demand for soybean meal, since it is the most important high-protein feed for livestock worldwide. The popularity of soybean meal as a feed ingredient is largely due to its high concentration of protein (44 to 48%) and its excellent profile of highly digestible amino acids. As a feed ingredient, the oil is extracted first and it‚Äôs typically viewed as a by-product. For this reason, soybean oil is the #1 feedstock for biodiesel in the U.S. and is also used in salad and cooking oils and industrial applications. A relatively small amount of whole soybeans in the U.S. are grown for food such as in tofu, edamame, soymilk, or other edible soy products.&nbsp; Although it is estimated that 80% of soybeans being grown in the U.S. are from genetically engineered seed (‚ÄúGMO‚Äù or ‚ÄúRoundup¬Æ Ready‚Äù), Vermont is home to a number of farms growing non-GMO and certified organic soybeans for food, feed and fuel.</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_column] [vc_column width=\\\"1/2\\\"] [vc_tabs interval=\\\"0\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [vc_tab title=\\\"Profiles\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362459966-1-58\\\"] [vc_column_text el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] <p>Here is where the profiles will go</p>\n [/vc_column_text] [/vc_tab] [vc_tab title=\\\"Reports\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362459966-2-51\\\"] [/vc_tab] [vc_tab title=\\\"Helpful Links\\\" tab_id=\\\"1362460022419-3-8\\\"] [/vc_tab] [/vc_tabs] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] [vc_row el_position=\\\"last\\\"] [vc_column] [vc_widget_sidebar sidebar_id=\\\"sidebar-9\\\" el_position=\\\"first last\\\"] [/vc_column] [/vc_row] \";}}', 'no'),
