(7569, 1, '2016-05-02 14:48:56', '2016-05-02 18:48:56', '<a href=\"http://www.uvm.edu/extension/\" target=\"_blank\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-7571\" src=\"http://vermontbioenergy.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/05/vermont_farmers_food_center-300x167.png\" alt=\"vermont_farmers_food_center\" width=\"300\" height=\"167\" />UVM Extension</a> and the Vermont Bioenergy Initiative supported the installation of a multi-source biomass fuel boiler at the <a href=\"http://vermontfarmersfoodcenter.org/\" target=\"_blank\">Vermont Farmers Food Center</a> in Rutland, Vermont. The boiler uses several alternative fuels, such as wood pellets and grass biomass pucks, to displace propane and heat the 4,200 square foot space, home to the Rutland Winter Farmers‚Äô Market and a variety of food system educational program and events. The biomass project demonstrates the economic advantages when compared to typical propane heaters, including a much smaller payback period (roughly 2-8 years) when using biomass fuel sources. Chris Callahan, a UVM Extension Agricultural Engineer, directed the project and worked closely with the Vermont Farmers Food Center to fit a biomass fuel boiler for the space specifications.\r\n\r\nCheck out this video featuring the project on Across the Fence, the longest-running locally-produced program in the US:\r\n\r\n<iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/6tp9qvKLJ8Y\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe>', 'Biomass Fuel Boiler at Vermont Farmers Food Center', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'biomass-fuel-boiler-at-vermont-farmers-food-center', '', '', '2016-05-02 16:16:26', '2016-05-02 20:16:26', '', 0, 'http://vermontbioenergy.com/?p=7569', 0, 'post', '', 0);
